        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1098218593" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8446469776897525066">Paris, 1878: Lydia Cassat is ill, dying of Bright’s disease. Thus she has lots of time to think. At the same time, her sister, Mary Cassat, asks her to pose for another painting. While Lydia poses, again she has a lot of time to reminiscent about life. Her thoughts drift a lot to some places in the US. Even when they walk the Parisian streets up to Mary’s studio, Lydia drifts with her thoughts intertwining the Parisian streets with the places in the US. Because of that the story is very scattere</span>
  <span id="freeText8446469776897525066" style="display:none">Paris, 1878: Lydia Cassat is ill, dying of Bright’s disease. Thus she has lots of time to think. At the same time, her sister, Mary Cassat, asks her to pose for another painting. While Lydia poses, again she has a lot of time to reminiscent about life. Her thoughts drift a lot to some places in the US. Even when they walk the Parisian streets up to Mary’s studio, Lydia drifts with her thoughts intertwining the Parisian streets with the places in the US. Because of that the story is very scattered. <br /><br />It is a small book, only 162 pages long, the goal of the author should be to pull a reader into this story from page 1. But on page 38 (end of chapter 1), the story continues to be all over the place.<br /><br />With the presence of Degas in Chapter 2 the story gains the badly needed guidance.<br /><br />The premise of the story is very interesting, centered around five of Mary’s paintings of Lydia. However, the story doesn’t have a good flow. It is pretty choppy most of the time. I couldn’t get into this story.<br /><br />Instead, highly recommend a novel about Mary Cassatt: I Always Loved You by Robin Oliveira<br /><br />@FB/BestHistoricalFiction</span>
  <a data-text-id="8446469776897525066" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

