  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3091311896" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3091311896" />
    <a title="Kara" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1288287-kara"><img alt="Kara" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1227469207p2/1288287.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3091311896?book_show_action=true">Jan 03, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kara" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kara" href="/user/show/1288287-kara">Kara</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1288287-kara?shelf=death">death</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1288287-kara?shelf=history-art">history-art</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer3091311896&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3091311896" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7234871220641259515"><br/>Imagine <i>Little Women</i> told from the point of view of Beth. <br/><br/>Or rather, a story about Louisa May Alcott as her writing was becoming well known, told from the point of view of Elizabeth Alcott as she dealt with the fact that she was dying and her sister was using their lives to become famous. <br/><br/>This is a historical fiction account of the Impressionist painter Mary Cassatt’s sister, Lydia, as she struggles with dealing with the fact that she is terminally ill. Lydia Cassatt was the subject of several o</span>
  <span id="freeText7234871220641259515" style="display:none"><br />Imagine <i>Little Women</i> told from the point of view of Beth. <br /><br />Or rather, a story about Louisa May Alcott as her writing was becoming well known, told from the point of view of Elizabeth Alcott as she dealt with the fact that she was dying and her sister was using their lives to become famous. <br /><br />This is a historical fiction account of the Impressionist painter Mary Cassatt’s sister, Lydia, as she struggles with dealing with the fact that she is terminally ill. Lydia Cassatt was the subject of several of her sister’s paintings and Chessman uses those paintings as a jumping off place, imaging what is was like to pose for each one as she knowingly got closer to her own death.<br /><br />Chessman does a fantastic job digging into the history of the Cassatt family, showing how much death and tragedy surrounded and affected the woman who painted pictures that short-sighted people are still today quick to dismiss as “too domestic.” <br /><br />The style of writing is 1st POV with a lot of stream of conscious thoughts, as Lydia describes how her day is going on, but also is constantly getting lost in a few form jumble of her memories, as if she’s not quite grounded to the present, which makes sense, as she grapples with both her own mortality and all the family and friends the Cassatts lost over the years. <br /><br />Lydia manages to hold onto the present just enough that the reader can follow her along as she muses on the past, but it’s clear she is on a different wavelength from her sister, blooming with health and bursting with energy as Lydia sees Mary’s career is starting to really take off. <br /><br />Lydia watches her sister paint as she reminisces on how the Civil War raged practically on their doorstep back when the Cassatt’s lived in Philadelphia, taking the man she might have married. And how the Cassatt family lost several siblings to childhood illness even as they lost neighbors and cousins and friends to the war, which will make you look quite differently at the some of the idyllic Cassatt paintings of mothers and children. <br /><br />When not thinking on the past, Lydia silently rages at the illness that’s destroying her, while also grappling with feeling guilty that her family has to take care of her. It’s tragically relatable, as so many people through the ages have probably had the same thoughts when struggling with an illness. Lydia also thinks about her sister both in terms of the art inside her that she is trying to get out, as well as the idea of making an impact on the world, and how Lydia helps and/or hinders with that.<br /><br />And, yes, I cried at the end. The writing and story were lyrical and beautiful and haunting and shamelessly tugged on the heartstrings as Lydia muses on what we leave behind as she gets ready to have to leave her sister.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="7234871220641259515" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

