<div id="review_2801204195" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2801204195" />
    <a title="Magpie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/45393593-magpie"><img alt="Magpie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1451799971p2/45393593.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2801204195?book_show_action=true">Feb 24, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Magpie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Magpie" href="/user/show/45393593-magpie">Magpie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title=" 9780712623636" href="/book/show/2702631-lydia-cassatt-reading-the-morning-paper">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2801204195" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7602697163403255568">Meryl bookclub 2020<br/>Meryl Bookclub 2020<br/><br/>“Lydia Cassatt reading the morning paper” was a little gem of a novel that deserved a bigger splash, the writing and characterisation were first rate and the story is still tingling all over me now, after many hours have passed.<br/><br/>Mary Cassatt (1844-1926) was the daughter of an American banker and an educated, well-read mother, both of whom believed strongly in the education of travel. (Sadly, some of that travel was to European doctors, attempting to cure thei</span>
  <span id="freeText7602697163403255568" style="display:none">Meryl bookclub 2020<br />Meryl Bookclub 2020<br /><br />“Lydia Cassatt reading the morning paper” was a little gem of a novel that deserved a bigger splash, the writing and characterisation were first rate and the story is still tingling all over me now, after many hours have passed.<br /><br />Mary Cassatt (1844-1926) was the daughter of an American banker and an educated, well-read mother, both of whom believed strongly in the education of travel. (Sadly, some of that travel was to European doctors, attempting to cure their son. He died. Of bone cancer). She spent 5 years of her childhood travelling around Europe and developed a determined pursuit to become a painter.<br />Her family objected to her becoming a professional artist, but her desire to study in the US and in Europe was supported and her family eventually moved to Paris with her to act as both chaperone and company.<br /><br />Mary thrived, moves into the sphere of the impressionists and formed a close bond with Degas that would last their lifetimes.<br /><br />But it is Lydia, Mary’s older, unwell sister and frequent model, who drives the poetic narrative. The plot explores the relationship between the sisters, famously devoted to each other, as Mary’s star rises and Lydia slowly fades away from (the ironically named) Bright’s disease.<br /><br />Each chapter moves the story forward by the use of a painting that Lydia posed for, and the colour pictures are helpfully included in the book.<br /><br />As Lydia languishes, she reminisces about her lost chance at love, the pain of war, of the family she will never have while remaining central to Mary’s existence and cheering her sister on.<br /><br />“How does one go about this business of living? I dwell on this question often, now. One’s life looks different, terribly sharp and clear, when one begins to comprehend the fact of one’s very particular, looming death.”<br /><br />Can art help us leave a little behind, something that means something to someone?<br />Does it even matter?<br />Most lives go unrecorded. But Lydia is still with us, driving, sipping, embroidering, and with lively eyes, forever reading the morning paper.<br />Luminous 🔆🔆🔆🔆🔆 </span>
  <a data-text-id="7602697163403255568" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


