<div id="review_2359173032" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2359173032" />
    <a title="Christiane" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/31207594-christiane"><img alt="Christiane" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1435263016p2/31207594.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2359173032?book_show_action=true">Apr 13, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Christiane" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Christiane" href="/user/show/31207594-christiane">Christiane</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/31207594-christiane?shelf=france">france</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/31207594-christiane?shelf=art-miscellaneous">art-miscellaneous</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2359173032" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8481687225397287481">This is a book to be read and enjoyed in quiet moments. It’s delicate and charming and moving and heartbreaking and full of light and colour.<br/><br/>Harriet Scott Chessman gives us a glimpse into the lives of Lydia Cassatt and her family and the Paris art world of the end of the 19th century, represented here by Edgar Degas. While posing for her sister Mary, Lydia lets her mind wander. Memories come up of her idyllic childhood, her old family home in Pennsylvania, the loss of several small siblings, her</span>
  <span id="freeText8481687225397287481" style="display:none">This is a book to be read and enjoyed in quiet moments. It’s delicate and charming and moving and heartbreaking and full of light and colour.<br /><br />Harriet Scott Chessman gives us a glimpse into the lives of Lydia Cassatt and her family and the Paris art world of the end of the 19th century, represented here by Edgar Degas. While posing for her sister Mary, Lydia lets her mind wander. Memories come up of her idyllic childhood, her old family home in Pennsylvania, the loss of several small siblings, her short time of love and happiness with her fiancé who died in the American Civil War. There are days of calm and almost contentment, of enjoyment of art, poetry and literature, appreciation of the beauty of Paris and delight in the loveliness of nature at the family’s summer home in Marly. And there are days of despair over her illness, her approaching death and the feeling of not having achieved anything durable. She feels grief over never having had a home of her own, a husband and children. Sometimes, for short moments, she experiences jealousy of her strong, healthy, talented and successful sister whom she loves more than anyone else.<br /><br />Here is my favourite passage :<br /><br /> “To live in that world you made, that creamy world of no difficulty, no blood. To know another’s touch, and to have children of my own ... and a life like a shell curling in on itself, glistening and clean on the sand, rolled in salt water, rolled and rolled, spent and spending.” <br /><br />There is so much in this book of so few pages : thoughts on life and death, love and family, memory and loss, art and creativity ... The reproductions of five of Mary Cassatt’s paintings of Lydia are the icing on the cake.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8481687225397287481" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


